# Vue template — test hooks (`data-test`, etc.)

Use this rule when adding or changing **attributes the UI tests locate**. It pairs with [playwright-tests.mdc](playwright-tests.mdc), which defines how `selectorList` and locators are written in `*.playwright.*.ts` files.

## What belongs here

- `data-test` values used by `appWindow.locator(\`[data-test="..."]\`)`.
- Special attributes used in this repo for menus, e.g. `data-test-test-menu` and `data-test-any-menu` on [AppControlMenus.vue](src/components/AppControlMenus/AppControlMenus.vue) (see [AppControlMenus.playwright.test.ts](src/components/AppControlMenus/tests/AppControlMenus.playwright.test.ts)).
- Optional `data-*` hooks asserted via `dataset` (e.g. `data-test-is-random` → `dataset.testIsRandom` in [FantasiaMascotImage.playwright.test.ts](src/components/FantasiaMascotImage/tests/FantasiaMascotImage.playwright.test.ts)).

## Naming

- Typically **lowerCamelCase block** plus hyphen-separated segments, e.g. `globalWindowButtons-button-minimize`, `dialogMarkdownDocument-markdown-wrapper`.
- Child components may use shorter or compound names consistent with that subtree (e.g. `socialContactSingleButton-image`).
- **Stay consistent** within the component and with the existing `selectorList` in its `tests/*.playwright.test.ts` file.

## Workflow

1. Add or update hooks on the template.
2. Update the component’s Playwright `selectorList` and tests to match ([playwright-tests.mdc](playwright-tests.mdc)).
3. Rebuild before running Playwright ([README.md](README.md)).

## Not in this rule

- BEM **classes** for styling → [vue-bem-scss.mdc](vue-bem-scss.mdc).
- Quasar / Composition API / script extraction → [vue-quasar.mdc](vue-quasar.mdc).

## Local types extraction rule

- For Vue (`.vue`) and TypeScript (`.ts`) source files, move small file-local interfaces/type aliases into a colocated `<filename>.types.ts` file and import them back.
- For JavaScript (`.js`), TypeScript (`.ts`), Vue (`.vue`), and JSON (`.json`, `.jsonc`, `.json5`) files, enforce expanded multi-line object literals via ESLint (`object-curly-newline` + `object-property-newline`) and keep files auto-fixable with `eslint --fix`.
